Angular distributions of gamma rays produced by neutron
bombardment of Al, Mg, and Si.
D(d,n) source

x4codes.hlp: Texas Nuclear Corp., Austin, TX, United States of America

x4freetext: The aluminium scatterer was in the form of a hollow
cylinder, 2.54 cm outer diam., 1.25 cm inner diam.,
and 5.1 cm long. The magnesium scatterer was in the
form of a solid cylinder, 2.54 cm in diam. and 5.08 cm
long. The scattering samples were positioned at 0.degr.
with respect to the incident deuteron beam direction.
During the course of each run, the neutron flux was
continuously monitored by means of a calibrated long
counter of the Hanson-McKibben type set at 90.degr.
with respect to the deuteron beam direction.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: The errors in the angular distribution data
are mainly the errors propagated through the
statistical deviations in the scatterer in and
scatterer out counts, the subtraction of the Compton
distribution from the gamma-ray photopeaks in the
spectra, and the statistical error in the long counter
counts used for the normalization of data runs.
However, the errors quoted on the absolute differential
cross sections also include the errors involved in the
determination of the long counter efficiency, the
efficiency of the NaI detector, the self-absorption of
gamma rays due to the scatterer itself and the error
caused by the Compton distribution due to
scattering in the sample.
